{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Arnsberg","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["North German and Swedish (of German origin): habitational name from a place called as ‘eagle's mountain’ (see   Arend   and   Berg  ), probably Ahrensberg in Mecklenburg. Compare   Darensbourg  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Arend","meanings":["German: from the personal name <i>Arend</i> of ancient Germanic origin, composed of the elements <i>arn</i> ‘eagle’ + <i>wald</i> ‘rule’."]},{"name":"Darensbourg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Aurore, Camile, Pierre.","Altered form, under the French influence in LA, of German   Arensberg  . It is formed with the French preposition <i>de</i> ‘from’, spelled <i>d'</i> before a vowel. This surname is found mainly among African Americans.","History: The progenitor of many of the Darensbourgs was Karl Friedrich Arensberg, a German born in Stettin in Pomerania (today Szczecin in Poland), who arrived in LA in 1721. By 1724, Darensbourg, as he came to be known, was de facto leader of the German colony in LA."]}]},{"name":"Gisela","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ or ‘scion’.  See  <b>Giselle</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Giselle","meanings":["name of Frankish origin, from the Germanic word <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. It was a common practice in medieval Europe to leave children as pledges for an alliance, to be brought up at a foreign court, and the name may be derived as a byname from this practice. This was the name by which the wife of  Duke Rollo  of Normandy (  <i>c.</i>860– <i>c.</i>930 ) was known. On her account the name enjoyed considerable popularity in France from an early period. Use of the name in English-speaking countries is much more recent, and is due mainly to the ballet Giselle (first performed in  1841 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gisela von Arnsberg was born in 1090, in Arnsberg, Hochsauerlandkreis, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany, her father, Hermann von Arnsberg, was 28 and her mother, Wiltrud, was 20. She married Graf Hermann I von Rüdenberg, Rüdenberger Burggraf von Stromberg about 1130. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1167, at the age of 77."},"et":{"1090–1167":"1090–1167","1090–Male":"1090–Surnud","1092–1144":"1092–1144","1125–1171":"1125–1171","1132–Female":"1132–Surnud","1135–Male":"1135–Surnud","1062–1092":"1062–1092","1070–1110":"1070–1110","1090":"1090","1110":"1110","1132":"1132","1062":"1062","1171":"1171","1070":"1070","1092":"1092","ABT 1130":"umbes 1130","ABT 1110":"umbes 1110","ABT 1132":"umbes 1132","1125":"1125","1135":"1135","1167":"1167","1144":"1144","um 1125":"umbes 1125","19 juli 1092":"19. juuli 1092","um 1135":"umbes 1135","Sachsen, Preußen, Duitsland":"Sachsen, Saksamaa","Arnsberg, Hochsauerlandkreis, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany":"Arnsberg, Hochsauerlandkreis, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Saksamaa","Rinteln, Schaumburg, Niedersachsen, Duitsland":"Rinteln, Landkreis Schaumburg, Niedersachsen, Saksamaa","Rinteln, Rinteln, Landkreis Schaumburg, Niedersachsen, Deutschland":"Rinteln, Landkreis Schaumburg, Niedersachsen, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1090–1167":"1090–1167","1090–Male":"1090–Kuollut","1092–1144":"1092–1144","1125–1171":"1125–1171","1132–Female":"1132–Kuollut","1135–Male":"1135–Kuollut","1062–1092":"1062–1092","1070–1110":"1070–1110","1090":"1090","1110":"1110